3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Aevo calculates ARB/USDT funding rates every hour using its off-chain order book to determine the premium/discount between perpetual and spot prices. The platform's rollup-based settlement ensures rapid execution while maintaining decentralized security. Funding payments occur precisely at each hour, with rates typically ranging from -0.1% to 0.3% depending on market sentiment toward Arbitrum ecosystem developments. The combination of maker rebates (0.02%) and hourly frequency creates multiple daily arbitrage windows."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ARB","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ARB's position as a major L2 infrastructure token generates consistent funding rate inefficiencies, particularly during ecosystem announcements or DeFi protocol launches on Arbitrum. The large trading volume on Aevo ensures sufficient liquidity for meaningful position sizes while the hourly funding schedule provides more frequent arbitrage opportunities compared to 8-hour cycles on centralized exchanges."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ARB/USDT funding rates on Aevo have exhibited distinct patterns tied to Arbitrum ecosystem events and broader L2 narrative cycles. During Q3 2024, rates averaged 0.05% hourly during bullish periods when new protocols launched on Arbitrum, reaching peaks of 0.25% during major announcements. Conversely, rates turned negative during general market downturns or when competing L2s gained attention. The hourly frequency amplifies these fluctuations compared to traditional 8-hour cycles, creating 24 potential funding events daily versus just 3 on most exchanges."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Aevo's unique rollup infrastructure creates specific arbitrage advantages for ARB/USDT traders. The combination of low maker fees (0.02%) and hourly funding settlements allows for delta-neutral strategies with enhanced frequency. Cross-exchange arbitrage becomes particularly profitable when Aevo's rates diverge from Binance or Bybit due to different trader bases - Aevo's DeFi-native users often maintain stronger directional biases. The platform's pre-launch token capabilities also create forward curve arbitrage opportunities when new Arbitrum ecosystem tokens are listed."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Trading ARB/USDT on Aevo involves rollup-specific risks including potential sequencer downtime and the platform's relatively concentrated liquidity compared to tier-1 CEXs. Smart contract risks exist despite audits, and the rollup's dependency on Ethereum L1 for final settlement can create delays during network congestion. Position sizing must account for lower overall liquidity - while adequate for most strategies, large positions may face slippage. The complexity of managing both perpetual futures and options on the same platform requires careful attention to cross-margining effects."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Aevo's hourly funding differ from other exchanges for ARB/USDT?","answer":"Aevo settles ARB/USDT funding every hour instead of the standard 8-hour cycle, providing 24 opportunities daily versus 3 on most exchanges. This creates more granular arbitrage windows and potentially lower funding rate volatility per settlement."},{"question":"What are the gas costs for ARB/USDT trading on Aevo's rollup?","answer":"Aevo's dedicated rollup typically costs $0.10-0.50 per transaction for ARB/USDT trades, significantly lower than Ethereum mainnet. However, bridging funds to/from the rollup incurs additional L1 gas fees that must be factored into arbitrage calculations."},{"question":"Can I use ARB tokens as collateral for ARB/USDT perpetuals on Aevo?","answer":"Yes, Aevo supports ARB as collateral with appropriate haircuts applied. This enables leveraged exposure while earning yield on holdings, though it increases correlation risk if ARB price moves significantly against your perpetual position."},{"question":"How does Aevo's pre-launch trading affect ARB ecosystem arbitrage?","answer":"Aevo often lists Arbitrum ecosystem tokens before mainnet launch, creating forward curve arbitrage opportunities between pre-launch contracts and eventual ARB/USDT cross-pair strategies. These require careful analysis of ecosystem correlation and launch timing risks."}]}]
